"1415–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1414–Male":"1414–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1388–Female":"1388–Deceased","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","about 1414":"about 1414","1380":"1380","ABT    1337":"about 1337","1405":"1405","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Hendreforfudd,Corwen,Merionethshire,Wales":"Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Twna","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian: from the female personal name <i>Tona</i>, a short form of <i>Antona</i>, a variant of   Antonia  . Compare   La Tona  ."],"variants":[{"name":"La Tona","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Sal, Antonio, Caterina, Gaetano, Gino, Matteo, Santo, Vita.","Italian (also <b>Latona</b>): variant of   Tona  , with the addition of the definite article <i>la</i>."]},{"name":"Antonia","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Antonia</i>, feminine form of   Antonio   ‘Anthony’.","West Indian (Dutch Caribbean): from the personal name <i>Antonia</i>, feminine form of Latin <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ). It is one of the surnames (compare   Martina  ) that reflect the partially mother-oriented name culture of the formerly enslaved people in the West Indies."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Twna was born in Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Twna ap Ieuan and Gwen ferch Dafydd. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Efa ferch Thomas."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1414–Male":"1414–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1388–Female":"1388–Surnud","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","about 1414":"umbes 1414","1380":"1380","ABT    1337":"umbes 1337","1405":"1405","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Hendreforfudd,Corwen,Merionethshire,Wales":"Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1414–Male":"1414–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1388–Female":"1388–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","about 1414":"noin 1414","1380":"1380","ABT    1337":"noin 1337","1405":"1405","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Hendreforfudd,Corwen,Merionethshire,Wales":"Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","1404–Female":"1404–Décédée","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1415–Male":"1415–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1337–Male":"1